choices.text: by walking, as we do every week…myself and the nearest and dearest, three legged Wrinkles. It is a challenge each time we negotiate this adventure and we scurry us along at a good pace. It is pretty funny watching my little handicapped dog getting a bus pass. The attendant lady is very tactful and makes us wait until she has gotten the most obvious customers off the vehicle. By that time we look every bit as hungry and in need of a bus trip friend, as does Wrinkles so we are able to slid onto an empty seat. As we travel along the strip to the main coastal road, they switch the engine off and let the solar panels do the work, so no pollution and a quiet trip. It isn’t too long, however for we arrive at the public car park by the coast where we cross to the other side. They fancy a change in walking surface though I’m not quite sure the dog of the house can manage the slope it is called upon to traverse from level to flat and so she is usually left at the till with our bags to be rung up. Many a wild and windy day it is safe enough to be left on the bus but not my wife who has a zest for life that, well she has this trouble called Leukaemia and if she were too feel an acceleration in the wind that people over the age of 70, don’t feel.
